in the novels of Thomas Mann. Using contemporary monetary theory as a background, the present study undertakes a close textual analysis to trace the meaning of money and awareness of money in the deep structure of Mann’s works. As Anna Kinder demonstrates, his novels reflect not only the latest in the monetary theory of their times, but also expose the uncertainty and allure of modern economic relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aEconomics in literature. 0aMoney in literature. 4aGeld. 4aMann, Thomas. 4aÖkonomie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aEconomics.  aMann, Thomas.  aMoney.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Literary and Cultural Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110637854oZDB-23-GLC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2013z9783110317350oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2013z9783110317251oZDB-23-DLW0 cprintz978311028849040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311028877340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110288773423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110288773/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2013  aZDB-23-DLWb2013  aZDB-23-GLCc2000d2014